The analysis of `outcomes.csv` reveals that **Treatment A** is the more effective treatment.

Although Treatment B has a higher aggregate success rate (~82.6% vs. 78.0%), this is a classic instance of **Simpson's Paradox**. When the data is stratified by patient severity, Treatment A outperforms Treatment B in both categories:
- **Mild cases:** Treatment A (~93.1%) > Treatment B (~86.7%)
- **Severe cases:** Treatment A (~73.0%) > Treatment B (~68.8%)

The aggregate result is misleading because Treatment A was more frequently assigned to "severe" cases (which have a lower baseline success rate), while Treatment B was more frequently assigned to "mild" cases.

The complete analysis has been written to `/output/analysis.json`.

